Assignment 2 - Time Series¶

Questions¶

What is your name? Include all team members if submitting as a group.

  • Archit Dudeja
  • Shreeja Kapoor

From what perspective are you conducting the analysis? (Who are you? / Who are you working for?)

I'm an analyst hired by the Airline company to create an forecasting model using their historical data to predict ticket sales.

What is your question?

The main question I'm trying to answer is: Can we accurately forecast future monthly international airline passenger numbers based on historical data?

Describe your dataset(s) including URL (if available).

Dataset name: Air Passenger Data Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ashfakyeafi/air-passenger-data-for-time-series-analysis/data Brief description: Monthly totals of international airline passengers from 1949 to 1960 Size: 144 observations, 2 variables

What is(are) your independent variable(s) and dependent variable(s)? Include variable type (binary, categorical, numeric). If you have many variables, you can list the most important and summarize the rest (e.g. important variables are... also, 12 other binary, 5 categorical...).

Dependent Variable:

Name: #Passengers Type: Numeric

Independent Variable:

Name: Month Type: Date/Time

How are your variables suitable for your analysis method?

  • The '#Passengers' variable is numeric and shows clear seasonal patterns and an upward trend, making it suitable for time-series model.
  • The 'Month' variable provides the time component necessary for time series analysis, with regular monthly intervals.
  • The dataset's length (144 months) provides sufficient data points for robust time series analysis and forecasting.

What are your conclusions (include references to one or two CLEARLY INDICATED AND IMPORTANT graphs or tables in your output)?

As shown in Graph (the time series plot), there is a clear upward trend and seasonal pattern in passenger numbers, with peaks typically occurring during summer months. Graph(ARIMA Manual) indicates that our manual ARIMA model achieves an AIC of 1254 which is less than AIC of Auto Arima, suggesting a fit to the data better than auto arima but not good enough for predictions. Adding an exogenous compenent to the model reduced the AIC to 1054 which is better than our manual arima

Graph(SARIMA Auto) indicates that our AUTO SARIMA model achieves an AIC of 905 which is less than AIC of Arima, suggesting a fit to the data better than arima and could be used for predictions as we can see from the SARIMA forecasting graph. Our manual SARIMA outperformed the auto SARIMA with AIC = 830 and more correctness in forecasting in test set. We can introduce exogenous variables in the model and see if that decreases our AIC.

What are your assumptions and limitations? What robustness checks did you perform or would you perform?

  • Assumptions:

The time series becomes stationary after seasonal differencing. Residuals are normally distributed and uncorrelated. The patterns observed in the historical data (1949-1960) will continue into the future.

  • Limitations:

The model doesn't account for external factors that might influence passenger numbers (e.g., economic conditions, fuel prices, global events). The dataset only covers up to 1960, limiting its applicability to modern air travel patterns. The model assumes that the growth trend will continue indefinitely, which may not be realistic in the long term.

  • Robustness Checks:

Performed:

  • Augmented Dickey-Fuller test to confirm stationarity after differencing.
  • Ljung-Box test to check for residual autocorrelation.
  • Analysis of ACF and PACF plots to confirm appropriate model order.

Would perform:

  • Cross-validation with different train-test splits to assess model stability.
  • Comparison with other time series models (e.g., Prophet, exponential smoothing) to benchmark performance.
  • Sensitivity analysis by varying the length of the training data to assess the model's dependence on historical patterns.

Stationary Test¶

Augmented Dickey-Fuller test

# Create a DataFrame to display the results in table form
adf_output = pd.DataFrame({
    'Test Statistic': [result[0]],
    'p-value': [result[1]],
    'Lags Used': [result[2]],
    'Number of Observations': [result[3]],
    'Critical Value (1%)': [result[4]['1%']],
    'Critical Value (5%)': [result[4]['5%']],
    'Critical Value (10%)': [result[4]['10%']]
})

We cannot reject the null hypothesis i.e time series data is stationary and therefore we will need to find about d parameter after differencing our data.

# Assuming you have a time series called 'Second_Difference' for the differenced data

# Perform the Ljung-Box test on the differenced series
ljung_box_test = acorr_ljungbox(df2['S_Difference'].dropna(), lags=[10], return_df=True)

# Display the test results
print(ljung_box_test)

      lb_stat  lb_pvalue
10  37.566382   0.000045

p-value < 0.05, there is significant autocorrelation in the residuals, rejecting the null hypothesis.

We know we have to increase value of Q, P and D.

Autocorrelation Function (ACF) plot.

Using ARIMAX¶

In [108]:
# Create an exogenous variable (trend)
df['trend'] = np.arange(len(df))

# Define your target variable
target = '#Passengers'

# Split the data into train and test sets
train_size = int(len(df) * 0.8)
train, test = df[:train_size], df[train_size:]

# Prepare the exogenous variables
train_exog = train[['trend']]
test_exog = test[['trend']]

# Define the ARIMAX order
order = (1, 2, 2)  # (p, d, q) - adjust based on your data

# Fit the ARIMAX model
model = SARIMAX(train[target], exog=train_exog, order=order)
resultsx = model.fit()

# Make predictions
pred = resultsx.get_forecast(steps=len(test), exog=test_exog)
pred_ci = pred.conf_int()

# Calculate performance metrics
mse = mean_squared_error(test[target], pred.predicted_mean)
rmse = sqrt(mse)
mae = mean_absolute_error(test[target], pred.predicted_mean)
r2 = r2_score(test[target], pred.predicted_mean)

print(f'R-squared (R2): {r2:.4f}')
print(f'Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mae:.4f}')
print(f'Root Mean Square Error (RMSE): {rmse:.4f}')

# Calculate additional metrics
mape = np.mean(np.abs((test[target] - pred.predicted_mean) / test[target])) * 100
print(f'Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE): {mape:.4f}%')

# Theil's U statistic
u = sqrt(np.sum((test[target] - pred.predicted_mean)**2) / np.sum(test[target]**2))
print(f"Theil's U: {u:.4f}")

# Plot the results
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(train.index, train[target], label='Training Data')
plt.plot(test.index, test[target], label='Test Data')
plt.plot(pred.predicted_mean.index, pred.predicted_mean, color='r', label='ARIMAX Forecast')
plt.fill_between(pred_ci.index,
                 pred_ci.iloc[:, 0],
                 pred_ci.iloc[:, 1],
                 color='k', alpha=.2, label='95% Confidence Interval')

plt.title('ARIMAX Model Forecast')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Number of Passengers')
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Print model summary
print(resultsx.summary())

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
